    "date": "2018-05-31",
    "comment": "Rationale: Proenkephalin-A is a precursor that is cleaved into 8 peptides, of which Met-enkephalin is one. Met-enkephalin is a major agonist of the Mu-opioid receptor.\n\nThe paper uses pre-embedding peroxidase immunostaining for electron microscopy to characterize the location of Met5-enkephalin in the rat Nucleus locus coeruleus. The majority of the peroxidase signal is found in presynaptic profiles (examples in figure 2-4). In the presynapse, strong signal was found associated with large-dense core vesicles (examples in figure 2-4). There was also peroxidase signal in the rim of small synaptic vesicles (figure 2 and text) in a subset of labelled terminals. Occasionally plasma membrane immunoreactivity was detected.. Experimental description: Four adult male Sprague-Dawley rats (Taconic Farms, NJ; 200-250 g) were used in this study.",
